The head of the ISC (Superior Public Finance Control Institution) said: "The control of pseudo-self-employment (in Czech " Švarc system ") has failed because of politicians.
In the area of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but is lagging behind in its application.
This is what Miloslav Kala, the Vice-President of the Superior Public Finance Control Institution, said in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be just and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking in us," Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of the Švarc system by Petr Nečas.
Mr. Prime Minister recently said that the ODS was not going to import entrepreneurs with controls; is it allowed or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it prohibits anything, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority responsible for inspecting the law," says Kala.
You referred to a Czech-German project during which public procurement legislation in both countries was compared at the check-up committee meeting in the House of Representatives.
What was the concrete question?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for the way in which public procurement and specific national legislation can be managed, as well as a practice itself.
We have gathered all this together and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more severe and better quality", however, according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continually develop more detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote itself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what results from it for you?
A common control of this kind should help precisely to stop us trying to clarify laws, reduce and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering the thresholds in the markets, we will not necessarily achieve this objective.
It may be that this system is so submerged by the paperwork, that those looking for the faults will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our ISC or a different organization?
As for the institutions, similar to the ISC, the Federal Accounting Court works there, which is organized similarly, it also has a slightly different council, but these two institutions are basically similar.
Skills are also, to some extent, similar, however, with a nuance in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure and therefore also has such accounts at the level of the different Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which is in our hands the resources of the state.
The public funds managed at home by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the rates of the Lands' accounts.
With regard to national legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Could it be because they have better inspectors?
No, I'm sure not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we consider to be a model, is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has meant to you, as an institution, to the amendment of the Public Procurement Act, that its effects are already felt?
As this amendment has come into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
As we do retrospective checks, we have to count with some delay.
Our observations relate only at the moment to the process of preparing future controls - we have launched a new instrument of "bad management risk detection" with which we have gone to the screen of nearly 14,000 public procurement - where these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been modified, as well as the conditions for certain types of tender procedures, and so on.
So do you consider the adoption of this law to be an advantage or an increase in administrative burden?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that may arise is that these rules become more severe and it is not possible to respect them.
Already under the previous regulatory regime, the claimant (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) was forced by controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the law on markets meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really useful to make the law more severe in this way?
No, not like that, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who commit formal mistakes without consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on administration.
So what's the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
