Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of the Agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had initiated close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to outer space started much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw, on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde book entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners behind and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The said Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) subsequently became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, and his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear if the rocket was to be used to drive or brake the drain.
The only information known about this Draisin is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with the professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaf Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents retained that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photo-electric hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects for the use of the rocket technique were carried out by the Interim Advisory Scientific Committee ("Tymczasowy Comitt Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war ended.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problememe, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and from the autumn onwards, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarakiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the Rakieta Meteorologiczna (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket of 1800 metres had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently an improved version was built, RM-1A and, in the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (known as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautics Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
The entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee were still to be mentioned two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and in 1978, the Miroslaw Hermaszewski pilot became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaute of the programme.
The repeal of the Law on Public Works is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Law on Public Works.
This decision raised a strong debate in public opinion.
There is no doubt that it is interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems geared towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of increased unregulated economic competition.
This means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free (without limits) movement of private capital combined with a fierce financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) create a tension on prices.
In this respect, the following meaning should be added: a producer seeks by importing low-priced goods to resist economic competition by making "priced" the competitor's price, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means, for most entrepreneurs, either to transfer production abroad, or to buy at low prices, or to disappear. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social costs of the state necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect misconception of masters to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so public that there is no need to provide concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital at home.
In other words, governments place their own population at the mercy of private capital without taking into account the collapse of society.
This is reflected mainly in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to force its own population economically to accept the dictatorship of private capital prices, especially in the area of wages.
This is due on the one hand to a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and, on the other, to the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour law.
The result is increasing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In RFA, there have been points of public food distribution for the poor for years that cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common that employees receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a supplement to reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse in society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to live up to poverty wages on the margins of society in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
Here we have to ask ourselves the following question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then, a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, to be tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the led economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital is in favour of the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory intervention.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not direct, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The evidence is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby that is present in all States.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national departments are delegating the development of draft legislation to industry-related law firms.
These bills were then adopted at the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as Western-type constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that the democracies oriented towards liberalism are now quickly faced with the situation described by Appianos in his book "The Roman Empire Crisis in the Time of Caesar and Pompeii": "The State was long in disquiet and the functions were attributed to violence.
The pots of wine, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The understanders and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with voices already sold" ... "The honest people did not in any way seek to obtain functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls". ... ' We really started to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that we had to choose an energetic man" ... It is true that Appianos had in the spirit of Pompeia, but it was Caesar who irreversibly turned democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in the antiquity, the current society is based on the preference of personal profit, regardless of the interests of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
As a result, today, as in the past, there has been a decline without the elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the 19th and 20th centuries' economic systems.
In the present state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises of which we are witnesses today and the crimes against humanity as we know them from past and recent history.
The repeal of the Law on Public Works is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at international and internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on government and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
