The movie Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamic students attacked the American Embassy in Tehran and captured 52 diplomats.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the positive outcome to the US administration, it could not, in fact, abandon Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempted liberation of the hostages by force.
Sequestrated diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate gave rise to a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential elections against Ronald Reagan.
The film Argo, from the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory in America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated periods, they returned to the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with rocambolesque coverage: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team who came to make marks for the shooting of a film with great science-fiction.
Combination of genres
The plan of the expert in exfiltration Tony Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is on the one hand a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a seistrise - such as in the trilogy Ocean's student, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres are successive: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been retransscribed into the film, there are no major differences),
Hollywood's lighter passages, irony-treated and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes of the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he has become a respected director and his acting game has ceased to generate ironic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film after the dark police officer " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that does not take place in his original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions at too many places
The director had to content himself with a subject that in fact offered only few palpative scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
It goes very well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is removed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track are drawn enough by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events at too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operatives, their characters would have earned a bigger place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it allows itself to be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
It leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in some way, uncompleted to date, and as an illustration of the exaggeration of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the matter.
