The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that the real adventures are not only about imagination. To convince themselves, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the mountain of newly erected books - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it does very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, an computer scientist in a large neighbouring company, said to us, "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one is willing to go to one of those ringing libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a town-dortort that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The community of 80,000 souls shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brain, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
For example, the city authorities realized that there was only one way to take a hand on statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the architect office of Rotterdam MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mind-provoking and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual witty and presented himself in the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a ricnation on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, disconcertingly and raising their shoulders, Maas, the scavenger, stacked his books of choice in order to make them a pyramid, and finished his talk with activist arguments supported by one: "holy!"
Here's my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or, as we say, Buchenberg!
Nine years later, the EUR 30 million mountain fell off the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and houses with a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the Book Mountain received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
This small, thorny township, which so far had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of an audacious lair, whose white facades invite you to think they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book under cheese bell.
Of course, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you sweep the ground of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverbers unequivocally speak the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking at the public benches, the dogs and the little boys and girls playing ball.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We completely changed the classical spatial configuration and opened the interior reading spaces to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been nicely furnished: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A special beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambris, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
That is how one day we found in an agricultural company friezes an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, one millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're making time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons and can then be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimetres.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary coffee offers us an amazing view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pots figs.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"This is incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in ecology," Trouborst said.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal means.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass façade serve as sun umbrellas, intercepting a large part of the beams.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
The completely automated blinds handle the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Buchenberg as "the soul finally found" by Spijkenisse.
In fact, a few weeks ago, during the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure filled the gaps in the library that were not yet fully covered (now it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are all over the place.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it is only for decoration."
For example, MVRDV has reached master's discipline, which is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new literary history page.
Even though it may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain from the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore meet on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still taunting to find that role, but they're on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
An external policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national cases.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other major powers: therefore, Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to attack public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
There is no doubt that this is a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is at least a decisive factor in the strategic thinking of Germany.
Does Germany suffer from its relations with the United States by opting for abstention in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not so serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Indeed, Germany has demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear vote.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences in opinion are not so great that they always appear.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from exhilarating with Netanyahou's policy.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore join a broader political line and must assert their unique position.
That is what they are doing at the moment in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been delicate.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she always have difficulties in taking leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking, for example, at the euro crisis, it is noted that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very diverse neighbours and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling that gap, so what remains?
The Germans simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, a institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
