Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial IST includes syphilis, chlamydia and blennorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common IST are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
The pubis lice and gale belong to the parasitic ISTs.
What groups are primarily concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhage often occur in men who have sexual relations with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men causes at least four cases of syphilis out of five reported in Germany.
In adult heterosexuals, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhage and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
There is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections among young people than among other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15-25 years.
Furthermore, in Germany, human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis more than doubled in 10 years: from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has decreased.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth over the previous year.
What are the symptoms of sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause genital abscess, urinary pain, white loss, lower belly pain, and the appearance of buttons and glass.
However, they do not cause any pain or other symptoms on a regular basis and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Preservatives may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect them 100%.
The reason is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricant infection or by close body contacts.
The experts therefore recommend that all persons who often change sexual partners should conduct regular reviews.
Most of the quickly detected IST can be cured and late side effects can be avoided.
