Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, reports prosecutors.
Prosecutors are trying to counter alleged abuse of Bradley Manning during detention.
The trial involves the detention of Manning in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning's sequestration has taken place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of decapitating thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors have tried to demonstrate Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the greatest leak of confidential information from the entire history of the U.S. Army -- has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that registrations of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints concerning his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring the Manning case to be closed on the grounds that the sequestration took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide during his detention.
This analyst of military intelligence, arrested in June 2010, is accused of having taken away thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed Manning was their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to a maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms, Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment that his guards reserved was "excellent" and that the treatment he had in the prison was "very professional".
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked him directly about his prison treatment, said Fein.
Manning replied that he had expressed an oral concern about some problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems mentioned.
"They wrote "no problem" (after addressing the concerns), and yet that did not mean that I did not raise any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to modify his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The military stated that they had given him this restrictive status -- a level below the close surveillance for suicide risk -- for its protection and safety.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was going well, and I wanted to be removed from this status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the Marine Corps in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and once passed away because of the heat.
He added that not knowing what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very scary.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said, Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, a cover, tongues, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the regulations.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned at night, they woke him up so that he could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a cover during the appeal.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had deduced from the order of his guard that he had to release his cover that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning would have told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his tie or tongue to hurt himself, but he had not.
That night Manning testified that his underwear, his tongues, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if convicted before a court martial, a trial that should be held early next year.
The defence stated that Manning intends to plead guilty to the least serious crimes and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should arrange for the conditions of detention to be justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defence.
If all charges are held, the accused shall be held in criminal detention for life.
