Laws for Neutral Cigarette Packages came into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of ill organs cover the dark green packages that are all identical, regardless of the brand
This law, which came into force in Australia, is a world premiere, logos and colours have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and the representations of children and babies whose diseases have been caused by the smoking of their parents.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between packages since Saturday is the brand name, printed in small characters on all packages.
This is the most stringent tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government stated that the goal was to deter young people from smoking by eliminating any glamour.
Studies have shown that if people do not start smoking before the age of 26, 99% of them are likely to never start smoking.
"Even when they're very young, children understand the message that tobacco manufacturers send through their branded image," said the Federal Health Minister, Tanya Plibersek, quoting studies that have, for example, revealed that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess."
While Australia has the lowest rate of smoking in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has put pressure on this law.
Tobacco manufacturers stated that this would boost the black market, which would provide easier access to cheaper cigarettes.
"This legislation will have adverse consequences," said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
The forgeries in China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others stated that the Act had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha from Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, said that the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to mask the horrific packagings, has increased significantly two months ago since British American Tobacco, British's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost to Australia's high court.
Ha said Zico sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is waiting for stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
The only problem, the experts say, is the popularity of social media and the population segment targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws prohibiting advertising on TV, sport sponsorship and the obligation for retailers to hide cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Web by companies and local sites, but it cannot prevent foreign sites from doing so.
"If you work in tobacco marketing and you only have a small window to promote your products, the Internet is an indispensable place for excellence," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman has noticed an increase in the contributions of some citizens lambda in favour of brands on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
