The Summit of the United Nations has concluded without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Fourth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration having been made public, although it has been announced previously and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Regular Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the United Nations Security Council, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit was closed, and then claimed that it would be published from one moment to another on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that the content of the text had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The lack of information between journalists was reported by the press officers of some of the governments of the United Nations that attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Later, the Peru Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Arab South American Summit (ASPA) and, although this was requested by the press, it had also not issued the declaration called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ISPA website, it can be verified that the document has been published in March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to establish safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited access to information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court, which sets a different borderline between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima filed against Santiago, which begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve today's disputes in this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piñera, giving President Humala a handcuff, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Bogota Covenant by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been suspended from Usur since 2011 after the resignation of former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly afternoon in Lima.
The representative read the outcome document, in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 project lines had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he noted that the countries of the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime would set up "important steps towards achieving the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "co-operation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to the low-cost Internet in all South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "Economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphant matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and provide a better future for our people," President Humala concluded.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the President of Peru in a speech.
Of these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the cross-sectional axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although it did not provide any more details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will enable its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and well-connected with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before beginning the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
