Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is my life"
Hetin Reyes basketball globe-trotter spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, travelled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemns him in the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros of Bayamón or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
"The basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this assertion.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind his itinerary out of standards, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he most affectionate is those who remind him of his appearance as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"It's been my best years, the ones I've most enjoyed because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
It has been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships fought from 1971 to 1975.
Then I retired during the 1981 championship, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been the leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying to me: "I have a cost-effective player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another one.
He was pleased with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the big manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of Mincy's expenses and duties on the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World, where we arrived at 4th and where we would have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't made us play the last game, said Reyes.
Is the World 1990 team the best national team you've seen?
She is one of the best, as was the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and put a tie on the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also young people (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy during the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Houruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all the predictions.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
Its statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculín did.
And this without taking into account his path in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Portoric leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Having been part of the nation's most glorious time between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What's left of you?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of the minor categories.
For example, Ponce's boys play only in their area and only face teams from other parts of the island during national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while this is not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for managers, field personnel and arbitrators.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch music from my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, attend basketball matches.
And of course, I take advantage of my wife's company, Isabel, which has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman's death
Larry Hagman, born 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas), made himself known worldwide by the leading role of John Ross Ewing, known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied a man without scruples, fearsome and manipulator.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil magnate without scrupulous J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday evening of complications of cancer, according to a news release from the family sent to The Associated Press for the Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing once again the ironic role he loved most," said the family.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who interpreted the role of her wife in the original series and in the follow-up, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said her press officer Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived his life in full," Gray said in a press release.
The doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis at Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had recognized that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995 he was diagnosed with malignant liver tumours and had been transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary type in the "Jinny of my Dreams" series broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In this, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two shows that have remained on the air for little time, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in cinema, there are well-received roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of J.R.'s deliciously detestable performance that Larry Hagman experienced his greatest success.
The CBS series on the Ewing clan and its relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspension around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode of November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant him and then threatened him to accuse him of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to assault him.
Hagman played Ewing's role as a corrupt and unsatisfied man but with charismatic smile: an dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who tried to imprison his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what to do as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Ci-gist the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, recalled this Friday of Hagman as a man "great, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
