A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that there he launched an irresistable hook: the end of the "great count" of the calendar Maya, on 21 December, to which many people referred as evidence of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax guff which some have nicknamed "the Debt Armageddon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought that the apocalypse would start.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said this week Professor Charmé to his Rutgers-Camden University students in New Jersey.
If we analyse what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and told, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is evil is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give classes on "the end of the world" this semester, which in theory will be the last of history.
In Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Wacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
"We analyse this because these ideas are growing over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, the Professor of History of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply called "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world did not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students have to study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed the day before the Apocalypse, which does not leave the students any choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world", said Restall.
The courses turned out to be quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, composed of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people can do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Infirmary, claims to have viewed all apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
